prj:ScienceGoal.prj:name: Lupus Class II Band6
prj:ScienceGoal.prj:note: 98 sources in Lupus. 2 basebands for continuum and 3 windows in 2 basebands for the CO/13CO/C18O 2-1 lines

prj:TechnicalJustification.prj:justificationText:
The correlator setup provides three high spectral resolution windows centered on the CO, 13CO, and C18O 2-1 lines as these provide the best diagnostics of the gas content in the disks. We use spectral averaging to lower the data rate while still maintaining sufficiently high spectral velocity resolution to resolve the lines and study disk kinematics.
The 13CO and CO lines lie near the edges of their respective baseband. We have verified with technical support via the Helpdesk that such a setup has been tested and is ok. The noise may be a little higher (10-20% depending on source velocity) than the OT prediction but there are no official guidelines for this and it would not affect our science goals at a significant level.
We also have two broad basebands to measure the continuum emission. These are separated from each other by almost 18 GHz to improve the image fidelity and provide some spectral index information. The LSB continuum window contains the potentially detectable 3-2 transitions of DCO+ and DCN which can trace the presence of cold gas and CO snowlines (Mathews et al. 2013, A&A, 557, 132), and we therefore use moderate spectral resolution, 1.5 km/s, for this baseband.

We have chosen a combination of resolution and maximum recoverable scale that can be achieved in a single array configuration (C36-5) and which allows us to study the inner disk at solar system scales (0.23 arcsec = 34 AU at 150 pc, corresponding to 17 AU disk radii) without losing sensitivity to the full disk (3.7 arcsec = 560 AU, corresponding to 280 AU disk radii). In this way we can efficiently survey all 98 disks and achieve our science goals in less than 3 hours of array time.

We aim for a sensitivity that would allow us to comfortably detect all disks in the similar Taurus region based on the Andrews et al. (2013, ApJ, 771, 129) SMA study. This can be achieved in less than one minute per source but our total telescope time is then dominated by overhead. We therefore choose an integration time of one minute per source which provides an efficient (<3 hour total) survey in which we expect to detect all disks in the continuum.
The corresponding line RMS is sufficient to detect sub-Jupiter mass levels of gas, as shown by our models in Williams & Best (2014, ApJ, 788, 59; Figure 2 of proposal). We observe at high spectral resolution because we can integrate in velocity without loss of sensitivity while preserving the ability to study disk kinematics.

prp:ObsProposal.prp:abstract: We propose to survey the gas and dust in 98 protoplanetary disks in the nearby Lupus star-forming region. This is a complete sample of all known optically visible stars with large infrared excesses and stellar masses > 0.1 solar. We will observe the CO, 13CO and C18O 2-1 lines and have developed models to derive gas masses. We will image with a resolution that corresponds to 20AU in radius while maintaining sensitivity over the entire disk. We expect to detect almost all disks in the continuum and measure sub-Jupiter masses of gas. From the resolved images, we will determine radial profiles of the gas, dust, and gas-to-dust ratio, as well as characterize the prevalence of dust holes and asymmetries. This efficient, large, and complete survey will provide an unbiased view of the gas and dust properties in young planet-forming disks, and is complemented by our VLT optical-infrared spectroscopic survey of the host stars.
